<subSubSection box="[198,861,152,178]" pageId="5" pageNumber="52" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,152,603]" box="[198,861,152,178]" pageId="5" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,333,152,178]" pageId="5" pageNumber="52">Etymology</emphasis>
:—Based on its occurrence in volcanic lakes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="52" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,152,603]" pageId="5" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,507,190,216]" pageId="5" pageNumber="52">Distribution and ecology</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rioual &amp; Gao &amp; Peng &amp; Chu" authorityYear="2013" box="[544,820,190,216]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="5" pageNumber="52" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="lacusvulcani">
<emphasis box="[544,820,190,216]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="52">Stauroneis lacusvulcani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found in the surface sediment of two volcanic lakes of NE 
<collectingCountry box="[298,370,229,255]" name="China" pageId="5" pageNumber="52">China</collectingCountry>
, Sifangshan Tianchi and Lake Xiaolongwan. Lake Xiaolongwan located in the Long Gang volcanic field in 
<collectingRegion box="[361,535,268,294]" country="China" name="Jilin" pageId="5" pageNumber="52">Jilin Province</collectingRegion>
, is a small maar lake (i.e. formed by a phreatomagmatic eruption) with a maximum water depth of 
<quantity box="[451,510,306,332]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="52" unit="m" value="15.0">15 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Chu, G. &amp; Sun, Q. &amp; Gu, Z. &amp; Rioual, P. &amp; Liu, Q. &amp; Wang, K. &amp; Han, J. &amp; Liu, J." box="[525,711,306,332]" pageId="5" pageNumber="52" pagination="108 - 118" refId="ref3976" refString="Chu, G., Sun, Q., Gu, Z., Rioual, P., Liu, Q., Wang, K., Han, J. &amp; Liu, J. (2009) Dust records from varved lacustrine sediments of two neighboring lakes in northeastern China over the last 1400 years. Quaternary International 194: 108 - 118. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. quaint. 2008.08.005" type="journal article" year="2009">
Chu 
<emphasis box="[583,633,306,332]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="52">et al</emphasis>
. 2009
</bibRefCitation>
). Sifangshan Tianchi, located in the Great Xing’An Mountains (
<collectingRegion box="[158,342,345,371]" country="China" name="Nei Mongol" pageId="5" pageNumber="52">Inner Mongolia</collectingRegion>
) is a much smaller water body as only a small pond, less than 
<quantity box="[1054,1098,345,371]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="52" unit="m" value="1.0">1 m</quantity>
deep, persists at the center of the crater. In both sites, the water is slightly acidic with low electrical conductivity and relatively high dissolved organic carbon concentration (
<tableCitation box="[512,601,422,448]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,241,389,412]" captionText="TABLE 1: Physical and chemical parameters recorded at the localities of the samples studied." pageId="5" pageNumber="52">Table 1</tableCitation>
). For Sifangshan, however, the values for total phosphorus (TP), total nitrogen (TN) and dissolved silica were measured on a water sample that was contaminated with sediment.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,152,603]" pageId="5" pageNumber="52">
In both surface-sediment samples, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rioual &amp; Gao &amp; Peng &amp; Chu" authorityYear="2013" box="[607,785,500,526]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="5" pageNumber="52" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="lacusvulcani">
<emphasis box="[607,785,500,526]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="52">S. lacusvulcani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is rare and represents less than 1% of the assemblages. In the sediment core from Lake Xiaolongwan, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rioual &amp; Gao &amp; Peng &amp; Chu" authorityYear="2013" box="[694,871,538,564]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="5" pageNumber="52" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="lacusvulcani">
<emphasis box="[694,871,538,564]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="52">S. lacusvulcani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most abundant (14.4%) in the sample taken at 
<quantity box="[151,238,577,603]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="52" unit="cm" value="400.0">400 cm</quantity>
core depth from the early part of the Holocene.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
